<HEADLINE>
FT  02 SEP 94 / International Company News: Restructuring behind rise to
IPounds 5m at Waterford Wedgwood
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MCMANUS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   DUBLIN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Waterford Wedgwood, the crystal and tableware group, yesterday announced
figures described by Mr Tony O'Reilly, chairman, as its 'best first-half
results since 1987'.
Mr O'Reilly said the increase in pre-tax profits, from IPounds 400,000 to
IPounds 5.1m (Pounds 5.04m), 'fully justifies the actions, initiatives and
strategies implemented in the past two years'.
Sales rose IPounds 13.9m to IPounds 149m, while profits before interest more
than doubled to IPounds 7.9m (IPounds 3.6m). Lower interest charges of
IPounds 2.8m (IPounds 3.2m) and a higher tax charge of IPounds 800,000
(IPounds 300,000) left retained profits of IPounds 4.3m. The group has taken
a charge of IPounds 1.8m for restructuring in both the crystal and china
divisions.
Wedgwood sales were up 8 per cent to IPounds 104m, while operating profits
more than doubled to IPounds 4.5m - the first increase in profits at
Wedgwood in three years. Wedgwood's earthenware pottery subsidiary, Johnson
Brothers, continued to perform badly,with sales reduced by stiff
competition.
The improved operating profits at Wedgwood reflected last year's
restructuring and improved sales in the US and UK. Sales in Japan remained
steady following price reductions, the company said.
Sales of crystal rose 16 per cent to IPounds 44.9m and operating profits
more than doubled to IPounds 3.4m due to strong sales in the US and Ireland.
However, sales growth of Waterford's mid-market Marquis range tapered off
after two years of strong growth.
Earnings per share amounted to 0.6p (0.02p).
COMMENT
Mr O'Reilly hinted strongly at a resumed dividend payment at Waterford
Wedgwood's annual meeting earlier this year. On the basis of these interims,
a nominal but welcome dividend of about 0.5p looks on the cards. The
reduction in debt to Pounds 58m puts gearing at 48 per cent. The company is
not fully out of the woods, however, as shown by the Pounds 1.8m
restructuring charge, and analysts are expected to leave their forecasts
unchanged at this stage. Most are opting for full-year pre-tax profits of
between IPounds 22m and IPounds 23m, equivalent to earnings of just under 3p
 -a prospective p/e of 23.5, reflecting recovery prospects.
</TEXT>
