<HEADLINE>
FT  02 SEP 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Tom Vernon says that a bicycle is not for going places, a bicycle is for
stopping, and that principle has already led to him presenting a string of
entertaining series. If you feel, as I do, that Fat Man In France which
begins this evening must be a repeat, the reason is that Vernon began as a
radio person and won awards for his 'Fat Man On A Bicycle' series which did,
indeed, include France. He begins his television series, now as director and
producer as well as presenter, in Brittany (7.30 BBC1). It sounded as though
Channel 4 had invented yet another way of avoiding the word 'repeat' when it
decided to call five programmes from the early 1960s The Lost Betjemans, but
there does seem to be some justification in this instance. Devoted to five
towns in the west country, they have not previously been nationally
networked. They begin (8.00) with Marlborough where the poet went to school.
The third series tonight depending upon the eye of the idiosyncratic
onlooker is Michael Moore's TV Nation (9.30 BBC2). It investigates the
peculiar passion of so many ex public schoolboys for the swish of bamboo on
buttock.
