<HEADLINE>
FT  02 SEP 94 / Fleet car buyers see discount cut
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GRIFFITHS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The discounts businesses have been able to obtain on most company car
purchases have fallen sharply. This is mainly because of vehicle makers
cutting dealers' profit margins and other marketing changes prompted partly
by a taxation regime introduced in April.
The mean average discount reported by a broad sample of businesses
questioned in this year's annual Company Secretary's Review of company car
schemes fell to 9.6 per cent from 12.2 per cent last year and more than 14
per cent in 1992.
Even the 9.6 per cent figure overstates the discount most companies are
obtaining, because it includes deals made by some companies at much higher
discounts. The survey says: 'The vast majority of cars are now being
purchased with a reduction of 9 per cent or less.'
The survey, covering 400 companies operating a total of 38,000 cars,
identifies a small number of deals in which discounts of up to 41.3 per cent
were reportedly received. Most companies - none of which is identified -
reported achieving discounts of 9 per cent or less on the same models.
The survey acknowledges that some figures reflect deals agreed before
manufacturers cut their dealers' formal profit margins to 10 per cent or
less from a traditional 15 per cent to 16.5 per cent. 'However, it is
apparent that certain car manufacturers, keen to expand their presence in
the fleet market, often with new models, have been offering fleet buyers
very attractive deals,' it says.
The average discount figure appears to suggest that dealers are giving away
all their profit on a sale, or even making a loss. In virtually all cases,
however, manufacturers are providing them with other forms of compensation,
such as sales volume-related bonuses.
The reduced discounts also do not necessarily mean that companies are having
to pay more for their cars. In many cases official 'list' prices of cars
have been cut.
Low list prices are welcomed by the motor trade because of the new company
car tax regime, which links tax payable by employees directly to the list
price of cars, irrespective of any discounts obtained.
This year's survey also dispels the impression that 'prestige' carmakers
like to give that their products are above the general car market's discount
wars. It shows most companies achieving discounts of between 6 per cent and
9 per cent on some Mercedes and BMW models, for example.
Company Secretary's Review of Company Car Schemes. Tolley Publishing, Tolley
House, 2 Addiscombe Road, Croydon, Surrey CR9 5AF. Pounds 47.50
</TEXT>
