<HEADLINE>
FT  02 SEP 94 / Clergy may lose security of tenure
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Consultations on whether clergy should become subject to conventional
employment contracts are to be conducted by the the Church of England.
At present more than two-thirds of the church's stipendiary clergy are in
post on the basis of the ecclesiastical freehold, meaning they cannot be
moved against their will. A steering group on conditions of service decided
this week to consult dioceses on seven possible alternative arrangements.
The church's policy-making general synod will debate the issue next year.
A report by the steering group finds that security of tenure in other
Christian denominations is 'considerably less' than that in most Church of
England clergy. It says the freehold enables clergy to voice their views
without fear or favour and protects them from arbitrary action by bishops,
fellow clergy, patrons or parishioners. But it impedes mobility and gives an
'unacceptable degree of permanence to the pastorally inadequate and
inefficient'.
Subjecting clergy to normal forms of employment contract are among the more
radical options raised by the report. Another option would replace the
freehold with a leasehold arrangement, under which incumbents would be
entitled to remain in post for a fixed number of years.
</TEXT>
