<HEADLINE>
FT  02 SEP 94 / World Trade News: Toyota signals hopes to step up China role
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHIYO NAKAMOTO
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Toyota yesterday gave the strongest indication yet of its interest in
setting up vehicle manufacturing operations in China, with the announcement
that it would establish a support centre for component suppliers there.
This came as Mr Tatsuro Toyoda, president of Japan's largest car company,
flew to Beijing yesterday, with other senior Toyota executives on a five-day
tour to strengthen ties with Chinese leaders and investigate the market.
Mr Toyoda, who is leading a group of Japanese vehicle parts executives, will
discuss the plan with the Chinese government and local vehicle makers.
The establishment of a supplier support centre is in response to calls by
the Chinese government for foreign manufacturers to help the country develop
its motor vehicle parts industry.
In July, China announced a moratorium on all new vehicle manufacturing
facilities until 1996 and invited foreign companies to extend support in
building up the country's components industry.
The establishment of a supplier support centre, where Toyota engineers would
extend technical assistance to parts suppliers, is not in itself a big
commitment by Toyota to the Chinese market. However, the move reflects
Toyota's interest in establishing manufacturing facilities in China, once
the government moratorium on new facilities has been lifted, and reflects
its belief in the potential of the Chinese market.
'It is a step looking towards the future and our ambitions for the Chinese
market,' a Toyota representative said yesterday. The company is considering
setting up a joint venture manufacturing facility in China, he said.
Toyota sold about 50,000 vehicles last year in China, or a quarter of all
Japanese vehicle sales in China and about 3 per cent of the entire Chinese
market of 1.5m.
The Japanese company provides technical assistance to a bus manufacturer in
Shenyang and an affiliate, Daihatsu Motor, extends similar help to a
passenger car maker in Tianjin. Toyota itself, though, has been slow to
express an interest in manufacturing in China.
It was not among a handful of foreign car companies - including Peugeot,
Volkswagen and Chrysler - which were quick to set up joint ventures in China
while such investment was still open.
However, the company says it now feels the market has enough potential to
justify local manufacturing.
