<HEADLINE>
FT  02 SEP 94 / Implants settlement approved
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A US judge has approved a proposed Dollars 4.25bn (Pounds 2.76bn) settlement
for women around the world who have suffered ill-health as a result of
silicone breast implants, Richard Waters reports from New York.
The decision, by Judge Sam Pointer in a federal court in Alabama, followed
months of deliberation and brought one step closer the biggest US product
liability settlement.
However, the deal could still fail. Some 15,000 women have already chosen
instead to retain their rights to sue the implant manufacturers in US
courts. The manufacturers have warned they will abandon the global
settlement if too many women opt out of it, though they have not indicated
what level of acceptance is needed for the deal to stay.
Under the terms of the deal, all women are automatically covered by the
settlement - and lose their rights to sue - unless they explicitly opt out.
The settlement is meant to cover women who have already experienced medical
problems and those who develop problems in future, though opponents claim
that the amount of money being made available is too small and will be
quickly exhausted.
In one amendment to the original plan made by Judge Pointer, Dollars 96.6m
of the settlement will be made available to women outside the US, up from
the original Dollars 81m, but critics still maintain that this is far too
little.
</TEXT>
