<HEADLINE>
FT  02 SEP 94 / Railtrack prepares plan for dismissing strikers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Railtrack is finalising plans to break the deadlock in the 13-week rail
strike by dismissing striking signal workers who refuse to accept new terms
of employment.
The company's chairman, Mr Robert Horton, is thought to favour an option
that could cost Railtrack about Pounds 16.5m in incentives to signal workers
to encourage them to defy their union and go back to work.
The signal workers would be offered a final pay and productivity package
that would raise their basic wage rates by up to 26 per cent and their
overall earnings by 10 per cent. In return, they would have to accept new
working practices to improve efficiency.
Last night, Mr Jimmy Knapp, the RMT transport union's general secretary,
said he found it 'astonishing that Railtrack would spend up to Pounds 16.5m
on signal workers when they could settle this dispute for a third of that
figure'. He added: 'My message to the signal workers is quite simple - stand
firm, refuse to sign any new contracts.'
While Railtrack said no decision was 'imminent' on new contracts, the union
fears the company will go ahead with its plan next week during the Trades
Union Congress.
After taking legal advice, Railtrack has prepared a detailed timetable for
introducing the new individual contracts for the signal workers.
First, a letter would be sent to the signal workers asking them individually
to accept the revised offer. Eight days later, a second letter would go to
those who still refused to agree, warning that if they went on strike again
they would be summarily dismissed.
After 16 days, if disruptive action continued, all remaining strikers would
be dismissed. They would then be offered re-engagement with a choice of
either accepting the new terms and conditions or returning to work on the
old conditions so as to treat them equally with non-strikers.
Railtrack hopes at that stage there would be large-scale acceptances of the
new conditions and the strike would crumble.
But the company is also preparing to face the prospect that a hardcore of
workers would continue striking. It plans to train new staff to take
signalling jobs but believes this option would depend on how many signal
workers accepted the new terms.
Mr David Armstrong, Railtrack's human resources director, also wrote to Mr
Knapp yesterday warning him that the 'legal deadline' of September 30 to
ensure signal workers secured up to Pounds 50m in pension fund benefits is
fast approaching.
Mr John Monks, the TUC's general-secretary, said yesterday he believed
Railtrack's policy of opening up more of the network on strike days was 'not
working' and he saw no end to the dispute.
'The company is not going anywhere in this strike. I don't see any sign of
this changing.' Mr Monks pointed out that while half the track might be
open, very few signal workers were defying the strike call.
ABB to shed 289 jobs, Page 7
Investors invited to run Tube line, Page 8
</TEXT>
