<HEADLINE>
FT  01 SEP 94 / International Company News: Philip Morris in Dollars 6bn
buy-back
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Philip Morris, the US food and tobacco group, is launching one of the
biggest share buy-backs ever mounted in the US.
The group's board yesterday authorised the management to repurchase and
cancel up to Dollars 6bn of the company's shares over the next three years.
It also voted to increase the dividend by 19.6 per cent, to 82.5 cents from
69 cents a share in the previous quarter
The moves sent Philip Morris shares leaping yesterday by Dollars 2 1/2 to
Dollars 61 - their highest level in more than a year.
Philip Morris prepared the ground for yesterday's moves in May after Mr
Michael Miles, the then chairman and chief executive, fell out with the
board over his support for a plan to hive off the group's tobacco operations
into a separate entity.
The idea was to lift the group's share price by relieving the company of its
controversial cigarette-making activities. But Mr Miles' successors - Mr
William Murray, chairman, and Mr Geoffrey Bible, chief executive - ruled out
a split, promising other methods of lifting the share price.
Stock repurchase programmes tend to increase a company's share price because
they reduce the amount of shares in issue, so increasing earnings per share.
They are widely used by US companies with cash to spare as a means of
delivering value to shareholders.
Philip Morris's cigarette-making operations produce particularly large
amounts of cash.
According to Standard &amp; Poor's, the US credit rating agency, the group as a
whole last year generated about Dollars 3bn in free cash flow - that is,
cash left over after paying for capital expenditure and dividends.
The stock repurchases announced yesterday, if fully exercised, would cost
Dollars 2bn a year, and the increase in the quarterly dividend would cost
Dollars 576m a year if sustained for the full year.
This suggests that Philip Morris should have little difficulty in funding
its new commitments from existing cash resources.
The stock repurchase plan is the latest of a series of buy-backs mounted by
Philip Morris. In November 1991 it authorised a Dollars 2bn buy-back and in
May 1992 it authorised a further Dollars 3bn worth of repurchases.
</TEXT>
<XX>
