<HEADLINE>
FT  01 SEP 94 / International Company News: Four-way merger sets up
entertainment giant
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The billionaire US investor Mr John Kluge yesterday unveiled a four-company
merger between his privately-owned international telecommunications group
Metromedia, the Hollywood studio Orion Pictures, the film and television
production group MCEG Sterling, and Actava, a cash-rich conglomerate.
The new company will be called Metromedia International. Mr Kluge, who
rescued Orion from bankruptcy last year, said yesterday: 'Our vision is to
create a new global media, entertainment and communications company.'
Actava, which after recent divestments has Dollars 215m in cash and liquid
securities on hand, will provide the capital for the new entity. Orion and
MCEG Sterling will produce new entertainment programming and provide a film
library of more than 1,000 titles (including Oscar-winning movies such as
Silence of the Lambs and Dances with Wolves).
Metromedia will contribute the delivery mechanism via its international
telecommunications systems.
Initially, the new company will focus on delivering entertainment
programming to overseas markets.
Mr Kluge will be chairman of the new company, and Mr Jack Phillips, a
telecommunications industry executive who was chief executive of Actava,
will be president.
The creation of the new company is the latest evidence of how
telecommunications and entertainment are converging.
Companies in both industries are eager to exploit technological developments
and regulatory reform that will allow films and other entertainment and
educational programming to be delivered to customers via phone lines.
</TEXT>
