<HEADLINE>
FT  01 SEP 94 / Lonrho vote on Rowland today
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT PESTON and ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Lonrho directors will today vote on whether to strip Mr Tiny Rowland of his
executive powers, in a move which may end his 33-year reign over the
international trading group. Although the formal agenda of today's board
meeting does not contain a motion to depose him as joint chief executive,
directors are expected to raise the question of whether he should continue
in the post as part of 'any other business'.
One director said: 'I am determined to push to remove him.' However, another
said: 'Betting against Tiny has always been dangerous.' The move to oust Mr
Rowland has been prompted by disclosures that he costs the company more than
Pounds 5.5m a year in salary, expenses and other charges under his direct
control.
Some directors are also concerned that the company has sold a recently
completed film about the Lockerbie bombing to an Egyptian company linked to
Libya, in possible contravention of United Nations sanctions.
Mr Rowland has increasingly been at loggerheads with his joint chief
executive, Mr Dieter Bock, a German developer who owns 18.8 per cent of the
group.
The board meeting, which will begin mid-morning in London, is expected to be
attended by all 14 directors. Mr Rowland can be certain of the support of
only two board members, Mr Rene Leclezio and Mr Robert Dunlop, both of whom
retire this autumn.
A simple majority of voting directors is necessary to strip a director of
executive powers. There is unlikely to be an attempt to remove Mr Rowland
from the board altogether, as this requires a notice to be signed by 75 per
cent of directors.
Mr Rowland may attempt to supersede the board by calling an extraordinary
meeting of shareholders. One of the group's biggest shareholders said
yesterday that if Mr Rowland did this, his institution would vote its shares
based on the recommendation of Lonrho's three non-executive directors, who
were appointed on Mr Bock's initiative.
The Pounds 5.5m annual cost of Mr Rowland includes a contribution of about
Pounds 500,000 to the costs of his two homes, more than Pounds 1m in
business expenses and Pounds 200,000 to pay for the education of dependants
of African politicians.
