<HEADLINE>
FT  01 SEP 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ITV's appeal these days is to the innate conservatism of the British public:
nothing here will shock or surprise you, everything is utterly familiar, any
new series will look exactly like an old series. This evening they begin
with a 22-year-old soap, Emmerdale, (7.00); move on to a 33-year-old nature
series, Survival, devoted today to animals that fly (7.30); then to an
episode of The Bill which began a mere 10 years ago (8.00). Downwardly
Mobile is yet another crass house-sharing sitcom (8.30); People Like Us yet
another lip-gloss mini-series from the US (9.00 and 10.40); and News At 10
is, well, News At 10. If you use television instead of Horlicks this should
do the trick. BBC1 and BBC2 are stuffed with repeats, ranging from The
Protectors, (11.50 BBC1) which was launched on ITV 22 years ago, to a nature
series, Realms Of The Russian Bear, which natural history freaks can zap
into the moment 'Survival' ends on ITV (8.00 BBC2). BBC2 alone has four
repeats tonight, but the best is on BBC1: the episode of French And Saunders
in which the girlies deliver a brilliant parody of the BBC's own 'House Of
Eliott' (9.30).
</TEXT>
