<HEADLINE>
FT  01 SEP 94 / BA silent over 'harassment' saga
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MOTOKO RICH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A retired police officer who has alleged he was harassed after making
complaints to British Airways was told the airline did not challenge his
account of the incidents, although it denied responsibility for them.
Mr John Gorman, a retired police officer, has alleged that he was the victim
of a series of threatening phone calls, robbery of documents and a beating
in his home since he complained of a condom in an in-flight meal in January
1990.
It is understood that in a meeting in July between Mr Mervyn Walker, BA's
senior lawyer, and Mr Gorman, Mr Walker accepted that criminal incidents had
occured. But BA said it had not 'been able to find out who is responsible
for what has happened'.
Mr Gorman said the abuse escalated after he reported a piece of glass found
in his drink during an in-flight meal in January 1993. In May 1993 he was
arrested for alleged conspiracy to defraud BA but it was decided there was
insufficient evidence to prosecute.
At least one of the allegedly malicious phone calls made in November 1993
has been traced to the offices of Mr Ian Jackson, then BA head of security.
But BA said Mr Jackson was away from his office on the day of the call.
It is also believed that some malicious phone calls made to Mr Gorman's home
have been traced to the Heathrow police station or to public telephone
booths within the station. The Metropolitan Police are continuing inquiries.
Last week BA passed on documents concerning its own investigations.
The police complaints unit has also prepared a report for the Crown
Prosecution Service.
</TEXT>
