<HEADLINE>
FT  01 SEP 94 / Lib Dem paper tackles low pay
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A regional minimum wage and the introduction of a low pay commission were
yesterday proposed by the Liberal Democrats as options to bridge the gulf
between the low paid and high wage earners.
The package of proposals, outlined in a discussion paper, Working for
Change, will be put to the party's conference in Brighton next month. The
two options are:
Establishing a regional minimum hourly rate of pay across the whole economy.
A low pay commission to investigate any industrial sector or company in
which it believed there was exploitation due to low pay. The commission
would recommend solutions such as a minimum hourly rate in a particular
sector or company.
Baroness Williams, the former MP Shirley Williams, who chaired the policy
working group, said: 'There are good reasons, if you are giving people
exactly the same standard of living, for some variations (in pay) between
one region and another.'
Mr Malcolm Bruce, Liberal Democrat Treasury spokesman, described Labour's
support for a national minimum wage as 'ill-defined and inflexible'. The
party is concerned that a minimum wage can destroy jobs if set too high.
The party is also proposing converting social security benefits to the
long-term unemployed into vouchers payable to employers taking them on.
The party has estimated that the cost to the state would be 'negligible',
and less than the cost of benefit and tax revenue forgone for the unemployed
 -an average of Pounds 173 a week.
Its document also suggests tax relief measures on the costs of child care.
</TEXT>
