<HEADLINE>
FT  01 SEP 94 / Exchange rules out Anglia action
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT PESTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Stock Exchange said yesterday that it would take no action against
Anglia Television's directors after reviewing the Department of Trade and
Industry's report on alleged insider dealing in the company's shares.
The exchange had been examining whether Lady Archer, an Anglia director, had
taken sufficient steps under its Yellow Book rules to prevent the leakage of
price-sensitive information and to ensure that her husband, Lord Archer, did
not deal in Anglia shares before MAI's Pounds 292m takeover of the
television company.
DTI inspectors had been told that on January 12, Lady Archer attended an
Anglia board meeting, at which the price proposed by MAI for the Anglia
takeover was first discussed.
On the following day, Lord Archer placed an order to buy 25,000 Anglia
shares on behalf of an acquaintance, Mr Broosk Saib. A further 25,000 shares
were bought for Mr Saib on January 14. On January 18, when the takeover bid
was publicly announced, Lord Archer ordered the sale of the shares, netting
a profit for Mr Saib of just over Pounds 77,000.
Anglia said last night that the exchange's finding confirmed its own
investigations.
The DTI said in July that it would be taking no further action against Lord
Archer, the bestselling novelist and former deputy chairman of the
Conservative party. It plans to issue a reply in the next few days to a
question from Mr Robin Cook, the shadow trade secretary, about whether there
is any legal impediment to the publication of the report if Lord Archer
gives his consent.
</TEXT>
