<HEADLINE>
FT  01 SEP 94 / More appeals likely against tax decisions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN, Public Policy Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A steep increase in the number of appeals against tax decisions is expected
to follow reforms to the appeal procedures to be phased in over the next
four months.
The reforms will make it easier to challenge rulings by Customs &amp; Excise and
open the procedure for appealing against the Inland Revenue to public
scrutiny.
The VAT and Duties Tribunal will for the first time hear appeals against
Customs &amp; Excise duty assessments from January 1. These assessments now can
be challenged only in the High Court, with appeals taking two years to be
heard.
At the same time, the special commissioners who hear appeals by taxpayers
over Inland Revenue decisions are opening their proceedings to the public
from today after nearly 200 years of secrecy.
Tax appeals to the special commissioners lodged from today will be heard in
public unless the taxpayer wants it to be in private. The commissioners'
decisions will also now be published, providing information to taxpayers and
their advisers that was previously available only to tax inspectors.
Judge Stephen Oliver, who presides over both bodies, said yesterday he
expected the reforms to encourage a higher level of appeals against tax
decisions.
He predicted that appeals against Revenue decisions would rise by 10 per
cent to 15 per cent as taxpayers and their advisers saw commissioners'
decisions. 'Openness will stimulate accountants, lawyers and advisers to
appeal against decisions which they had previously thought were beyond
challenge,' he said.
On Customs &amp; Excise duties, the judge estimated that the tribunal might
attract 160 to 200 appeals a year compared with the four or five cases which
come to the High Court under the present arrangements.
The tribunal will be able to review a wide range of administrative decisions
by Customs &amp; Excise relating to duties. These include licensing arrangements
for bonded warehouses, the imposition of anti-dumping duties and deadlines
for payment of duties.
The tribunal will also hear appeals over two new taxes introduced in the
November Budget last year: the insurance premium tax from October 1, and the
air passenger duty from November 1.
Judge Oliver said he planned to recruit new members to reflect the expansion
of the tribunal's remit. Representative bodies affected by Customs &amp; Excise
duties, insurance premium tax and air passenger duty would be invited to put
names forward.
He also intended to create a users' committee to advise him on the work of
the special commissioners. This would review their rules and procedures and
make recommendations about facilities for those appearing before the
commissioners.
</TEXT>
<XX>
