<HEADLINE>
FT  01 SEP 94 / Two radio stations to open today
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Five new large regional commercial radio stations capable of reaching more
than 15m people are being launched over the next fortnight, the first two
going on air today.
The FM stations, aimed at adults, are staging the UK's largest number of
virtually simultaneous radio launches.
The stations should boost commercial radio's 47.4 per cent share of total
listening, put further competitive pressure on the BBC, and encourage growth
in radio's 4 per cent share of total advertising.
The largest of the new stations, JFM 100.4 Northwest, launches today with a
mix of blues, soul, rhythm and blues and jazz. It will be able to be heard
by about 6m people in the north-west.
Mr Peter Salt, managing director of the new station, which is a subsidiary
of Golden Rose Communications, said yesterday he had received more than 800
letters of appreciation from people who had heard test transmissions.
Heart FM, which will launch on September 6, will specialise in soft adult
contemporary music. Up to 3m people in Warwickshire and the west Midlands
will receive the station. Heart, which is owned by Chrysalis, the media
group, has already taken more than Pounds 300,000 in advance advertising
bookings.
Century Radio, a wholly owned subsidiary of Border Television, will be aimed
at the north-east. It also launches today with a mixture of speech, music
and well-known broadcasters such as Simon Bates and James Whale.
Galaxy Radio goes on air on September 4 with a mixture of classic and
contemporary dance music and local and national news to about 2m listeners
in the Severn estuary area in the south-west.
The last of the five to go on air will be Scot Radio on September 16,
broadcasting to central Scotland.
The station, whose main shareholders are Border and Grampian Television,
should be able to reach 70 per cent of the Scottish population with a
mixture of music, and news, phone-ins and conversation during the day.
</TEXT>
