<HEADLINE>
FT  01 SEP 94 / Union check-off shortfall reported
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Between 600,000 and 1.2m of the 6m trade unionists who pay their
subscriptions through the check-off system for deducting dues from wages had
still not signed new instructions to do so by the beginning of last month,
the independent Labour Research Department said yesterday.
Under the Trade Union Reform and Employment Rights Act 1993 union members
who pay through check-off had to confirm their desire to continue paying in
this way by yesterday. The unions will have to repeat this exercise every
three years.
A survey by the department found that very few members had refused to
confirm, but many unions were having difficulty contacting remaining
members.
In the AEEU engineering union, refusals are running at only 0.5 per cent of
the membership but the union is still nearly 20 per cent, or 160,000
members, short of a full sign-up. Just 414 of the 55,416 members of the IRSF
tax officers union had decided not to re-sign.
The public-service union Unison, Britain's largest union, said yesterday
that around 130,000 of its 1.3m members had still to re-sign.
Three unions encouraged their members to switch from check-off to direct
debit payment of their subscriptions. The NUT teaching union persuaded 65
per cent of its members to switch to direct debit, the banking union Bifu
had a 56 per cent conversion and Natfhe, the lecturers' union, had a 47 per
cent conversion.
The survey found that 12 employers had withdrawn check-off facilities
including the Bank of England, Royal Bank of Scotland, Barclays (from
November) and BAA, the airports group.
Labour Research, 78 Blackfriars Road, London SE1 8HS. Pounds 2.40.
</TEXT>
