<HEADLINE>
FT  01 SEP 94 / Monks expected to address Lib Dems: Break with tradition may
invite criticism at TUC
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr John Monks, the Trades Union Congress general secretary, is expected to
break with tradition and address the Liberal Democrats' conference later
this month.
He will also address a fringe meeting at the Conservative party conference.
Mr Monks is keen to loosen the trade union movement's special ties with the
Labour party in favour of a more broad lobbying role with close ties to the
main parties and the government. He continued to stress this modernisation
strategy yesterday at the launch of a TUC-commissioned book by Robert
Taylor, labour correspondent of the Financial Times.
The TUC general secretary said trade unions should support rights for all
workers - not just union members. 'As champions of workplace rights for all,
unions can help to restore the balance between capital and labour that has
been upset by 15 years of hostile anti-union legislation,' he said.
He added: 'The immediate outlook is difficult but the unions are adaptable
and pragmatic enough to grow.'
His policies have their opponents in the trade union movement and Mr Monks'
decision to address parties other than Labour may attract criticism at next
week's TUC Congress.
He has received an 'open-ended' invitation from the Liberal Democrats to
speak to the full conference or to a fringe meeting. Mr Monks also said
yesterday that he had accepted an invitation from the Law Society to speak
at a fringe meeting at the Conservative conference.
Both Mr Monks and Mr Tony Blair, the Labour leader, believe that a greater
distance between the trade unions and the Labour party would be to their
mutual advantage.
However some union officials have raised objections to the close relations
Mr Monks has been trying to foster with government ministers.
The three main TUC-affiliated unions - Unison, the public-service union and
the TGWU and the GMB , the two general unions - all objected to an
invitation to Mr David Hunt, then employment secretary, to attend a
TUC-organised conference on full employment in July.
The arrival of Mr Michael Portillo to replace Mr Hunt makes a close
relationship between the TUC leader and the employment secretary less
likely, although Mr Monks has had an introductory meeting with Mr Portillo.
Bedrock unionism, Page 22
</TEXT>
